	key === best ? `<strong>${value}</strong>` : value;

const baseUrl = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/?$/, '/');
const samplePanelPath = `${baseUrl}figures/context-memory-tepa-seed17-sample-panel.png`;
---

<Layout title={title} description={description}>
	<header class="hero">
		<nav class="topbar" aria-label="Primary">
			<a href="#results">Results</a>
			<a href="#analysis">Analysis</a>
		</nav>
		<div class="hero-inner">
			<p class="kicker">Technical note | May 28, 2026</p>
			<h1>Free-form action conditioning for JEPA-style world models</h1>
			<p class="standfirst">
				A small empirical note on whether the action term in models like LeWorldModel can
				become a flexible condition encoder for general-purpose prediction and perception.
			</p>
			<div class="summary-grid" aria-label="Summary">
				<div>
					<span>Motivation</span>
					<p>General-purpose prediction models need instructions, not only typed action vectors.</p>
				</div>
				<div>
					<span>First question</span>
					<p>Can context and condition both be flexible encoders and still predict good targets?</p>
				</div>
				<div>
					<span>Current answer</span>
					<p>Yes in a toy setting, but architectural superiority is not yet established.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
	</header>

	<main class="page">
		<aside class="toc" aria-label="Contents">
			<p>Contents</p>
			<a href="#abstract">Abstract</a>
			<a href="#motivation">Motivation</a>
			<a href="#setup">Setup</a>
			<a href="#models">Models</a>
			<a href="#results">Results</a>
			<a href="#analysis">Analysis</a>
			<a href="#next">Next tests</a>
			<a href="#references">References</a>
		</aside>

		<article class="note">
			<section id="abstract" class="lede">
				<h2>Abstract</h2>
				<p>
					This project was inspired by LeWorldModel's use of an explicit action term. That
					choice gives the model a powerful handle for action-conditioned prediction, but it also
					keeps the interface grounded in a domain-specific action space. The question here is
					whether that action term can be generalized into a flexible, free-form condition input.
					If a world model is meant to support general-purpose prediction and perception, its
					input interface has to span structured actions, natural language, transformations,
					goals, horizons, and other condition surfaces. The model sees context, receives a
					condition, and predicts what follows.
				</p>
				<p>
					The experiment uses a deterministic 2D puck-world benchmark. A rendered scene is paired
					with a condition describing an intervention, and the model predicts a latent target for
					the resulting rollout. The comparison includes standard Tri-Embedding Predictive
					Architecture (TEPA), context-memory TEPA, a context-stuffed JEPA baseline, and a fine-tuned
					condition-encoder variant. The result is evidence of capability, not proof of
					architectural superiority: flexible condition encoders can produce quality
					JEPA-style predictions in this setting, and the next question is how to organize the
					architecture.
				</p>
			</section>

			<section id="motivation">
				<h2>Motivation</h2>
				<p>
					LeWorldModel is close to the desired shape of a general-purpose prediction model: it
					conditions latent world prediction on an action. The missing piece is flexibility. A
					domain-specific action vector is appropriate for a control benchmark, but a foundation
					world model should accept many ways of specifying what to predict.
				</p>
				<p>
					The basic interface should look familiar from LLM prompting, but the native output is a
					predicted latent consequence rather than text. The context says what is present. The
					condition says what action, transformation, query, horizon, or goal should matter. The
					target latent can then support downstream decoders, probes, retrieval, planning, or task
					specific heads.
				</p>
				<p>
					The hypothesis is that the condition can be represented by an embedding module. That
					embedding should carry the information needed to apply the requested transformation to
					the context. TEPA is the proposed architectural answer explored here: keep context,
					condition, and target as distinct embeddings, then test whether that factorization
					preserves prediction quality while improving flexibility, reuse, and diagnostics. The
					name is meant to acknowledge the JEPA lineage while marking the extra condition term
					as the object of study.
				</p>
			</section>

			<section id="setup">
				<h2>Setup</h2>
				<GeneratedDiagram diagram={actionConditioningNoteDiagram} />
				<p>
					The first question is whether both the context and the condition can be treated as
					flexible encoders while still producing quality JEPA-style target predictions. The
					follow-up questions are architectural: how should the model combine them, and do the
					benefits of factoring the condition out of the context outweigh the costs?
				</p>
				<div class="pseudocode-set" aria-label="Architecture pseudocode">
					<div class="pseudo-block">
						<h3>Standard TEPA</h3>
						<pre><code>z_context = E_context(x)  # cache once

for c in C:
  z_condition = E_condition(c)
  z_hat_target[c] = P(z_context, z_condition)</code></pre>
					</div>
					<div class="pseudo-block">
						<h3>Context-Memory TEPA</h3>
						<pre><code>M_context = E_context_memory(x)  # cache once

for c in C:
  z_condition = E_condition(c)
  z_readout = CrossAttention(
    query = z_condition,
    keys = M_context,
    values = M_context
  )
  z_hat_target[c] = P(z_condition, z_readout)</code></pre>
					</div>
					<div class="pseudo-block">
						<h3>Context-Stuffed JEPA</h3>
						<pre><code>for c in C:
  joint_input = Pack(x, c)
  z_joint = E_joint(joint_input)
  z_hat_target[c] = P(z_joint)</code></pre>
					</div>
				</div>
				<p class="shared-objective">
					In this benchmark, all three architectures predict the same target representation. The
					current runs use SIGReg during target autoencoder pretraining, then freeze that target
					path for predictor training:
				</p>
				<pre class="compact-code"><code>z_target = E_target(y_c)
loss_target =
  recon(D_target(z_target), y_c)
  + lambda_sig * SIGReg(z_target)

loss_predict =
  d(z_hat_target, stopgrad(z_target))</code></pre>
				<p>
					For unfrozen or end-to-end variants, the same SIGReg pressure can remain in the
					predictor objective when the target path is trainable; it is an anti-collapse pressure
					on the latent space, not a difference between the three architecture diagrams above.
				</p>
				<p>
					The condition is a structured intervention in the current benchmark and can later expand
					to natural language, demonstrations, goals, horizons, or other query surfaces.
					The target side is intentionally explicit. The training target is not raw prose. It is a
					conditioned outcome bundle produced by the simulator, encoded by a separately pretrained
					target encoder. That gives the predictor a stable latent target instead of asking it to
					invent a target space while also learning the dynamics.
				</p>
				<figure class="sample-panel">
					<img
						src={samplePanelPath}
						alt="Puck-world qualitative prediction panel with context, decoded target, and prediction views."
						loading="lazy"
					/>
					<figcaption>
						Qualitative sample panel from a context-memory TEPA run. It is useful for error
						inspection, while the table below is the stronger evidence.
					</figcaption>
				</figure>
			</section>

			<section id="models">
				<h2>Models Compared</h2>
				<div class="model-list">
					<section>
						<h3>Standard TEPA</h3>
						<p>
							The proposed tri-embedding architecture in its simplest form: separate context,
							condition, and target embeddings with a predictor between them. It can encode the
							context once, cache one compact context vector, and apply a variable number of
							conditions against that vector.
						</p>
					</section>
					<section>
						<h3>Context-Memory TEPA</h3>
						<p>
							A factorized model that replaces the single-vector context cache with reusable
							context memory tokens. The condition reads from that memory through cross-attention,
							so condition-specific details can be selected after the condition is known.
						</p>
					</section>
					<section>
						<h3>Context-Stuffed JEPA Baseline</h3>
						<p>
							This is essentially a JEPA-style baseline for this benchmark: it predicts the same
							target latent, but stuffs context and condition into one trainable joint encoder.
							It is a strong comparator because the joint encoder can become purpose-built for
							the task.
						</p>
					</section>
					<section>
						<h3>Fine-Tuned Condition TEPA</h3>
						<p>
							A context-memory TEPA variant initialized from the pretrained condition encoder,
							then allowed to update condition weights during predictor training at a reduced
							learning rate. Fine-tuned weights are saved separately from the original pretrained
							checkpoint.
						</p>
					</section>
				</div>
			</section>

			<section id="results">
				<h2>Three-Seed Results</h2>
				<p>
					Values are mean +/- standard deviation across seeds 17, 43, and 101. Bold cells mark
					the current winner for each metric. The joint-encoder baseline is named here as a
					context-stuffed JEPA baseline because it preserves the JEPA-style latent prediction
					objective while combining condition and context upstream.
				</p>
				<div class="table-wrap">
					<table>
						<thead>
							<tr>
								<th>Metric</th>
								<th>Direction</th>
								<th>Standard TEPA</th>
								<th>Context-Memory TEPA</th>
								<th>Context-Stuffed JEPA</th>
								<th>Fine-Tuned Condition TEPA</th>
							</tr>
						</thead>
						<tbody>
							{
								results.map((row) => (
									<tr>
										<td class="metric-cell">{row.metric}</td>
										<td data-label="Direction">{row.direction}</td>
										<td
											data-label="Standard TEPA"
											set:html={renderValue(row.standard, 'standard', row.best)}
										></td>
										<td
											data-label="Context-Memory TEPA"
											set:html={renderValue(row.memory, 'memory', row.best)}
										></td>
										<td
											data-label="Context-Stuffed JEPA"
											set:html={renderValue(row.jepa, 'jepa', row.best)}
										></td>
										<td
											data-label="Fine-Tuned Condition TEPA"
											set:html={renderValue(row.finetuned, 'finetuned', row.best)}
										></td>
									</tr>
								))
							}
						</tbody>
					</table>
				</div>
			</section>

			<section id="analysis">
				<h2>Analysis</h2>
				<h3>Can flexible condition encoders produce quality JEPA-style predictions?</h3>
				<p>
					The current answer is yes, within the limits of this structured-only puck-world
					benchmark. Standard TEPA, context-memory TEPA, and the context-stuffed JEPA baseline all
					learn to predict the same SIGReg-shaped target space. That supports the first premise:
					an action-like condition does not have to be a fixed typed vector to participate in a
					JEPA-style prediction objective. It does not yet prove generality across natural
					language, mixed formats, or many domains.
				</p>
				<h3>How should the architecture handle the condition?</h3>
				<p>
					The results point toward interaction capacity as the main design pressure. Standard
					TEPA is the cleanest factorization, but its single context vector can become a bottleneck.
					Context-memory TEPA keeps the condition path separate while letting the condition read
					from richer cached context memory, and it is the strongest current factorized model.
					Fine-tuning the condition encoder improves in-domain validation and latent probe scores,
					but does not uniformly improve counterfactual target error, so condition adaptation
					should be treated as useful but not settled.
				</p>
				<h3>Do the benefits of factoring condition from context outweigh the costs?</h3>
				<p>
					Not proven yet. The performance is close enough that the claim should not be
					"TEPA is more accurate." The stronger claim is narrower: TEPA-style factorization can
					preserve competitive prediction quality while offering a reusable condition interface,
					context caching, and cleaner diagnostics. The context-stuffed JEPA baseline remains a
					strong alternative because its joint encoder can specialize to the task and perform
					early context-condition interaction. If a workload needs one condition per context,
					context stuffing may be the simpler choice. If a workload needs many actions, queries,
					or counterfactuals over the same context, factorized TEPA variants become more
					attractive.
				</p>
			</section>

			<section id="next">
				<h2>Next Tests</h2>
				<div class="next-grid">
					<div>
						<h3>Identifiability under action conditioning</h3>
						<p>
							Measure whether predicted latents recover simulator state, action parameters, and
							future outcomes through simple linear probes and alignment tests.
						</p>
					</div>
					<div>
						<h3>Condition encoder ablations</h3>
						<p>
							Compare frozen, fine-tuned, delayed-unfreeze, and scratch condition encoders on the
							same fixed target space.
						</p>
					</div>
					<div>
						<h3>Flexible condition surfaces</h3>
						<p>
							Reintroduce JSON, YAML, key-value text, and natural-language templates after the
							structured-only benchmark is stable.
						</p>
					</div>
					<div>
						<h3>Amortized counterfactual sweeps</h3>
						<p>
							Encode one context once, evaluate many conditions, and compare the standard TEPA
							vector cache, the context-memory cache, and the context-stuffed JEPA baseline on
							quality, latency, and memory.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</section>

			<section id="references">
				<h2>References</h2>
				<ol class="references">
					<li>
						Klindt, D., LeCun, Y., and Balestriero, R. (2026). When Does LeJEPA Learn a
						World Model? The Role of Identifiability in Latent Space Feature Learning.
						<a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2605.26379">arXiv:2605.26379</a>.
						<a href="https://klindtlab.github.io/lejepa-identifiability/">Project page</a>.
					</li>
					<li>
						Maes, L., Le Lidec, Q., Scieur, D., LeCun, Y., and Balestriero, R. (2026).
						LeWorldModel: Stable End-to-End Joint-Embedding Predictive Architecture from
						Pixels. <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.19312">arXiv:2603.19312</a>.
					</li>
					<li>
						Balestriero, R., and LeCun, Y. (2025). LeJEPA: Provable and Scalable
						Self-Supervised Learning Without the Heuristics.
						<a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2511.08544">arXiv:2511.08544</a>.
					</li>
					<li>
						Assran, M. et al. (2023). Self-Supervised Learning from Images with a
						Joint-Embedding Predictive Architecture.
						<a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2301.08243">arXiv:2301.08243</a>.
					</li>
				</ol>
			</section>
		</article>
	</main>
</Layout>

